                <note rend="inline" type="source">710.Consultation(2)/433: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="73" xml:id="d307fn1">This message was repeated to the American Delegate
                        at Habana in Department’s telegram No. 26, July 25, 2 p.m.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-24T15:00:00-03:00"
                            >July 24, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>366. Nabuco<note n="74" xml:id="d307fn2">Mauricio Nabuco, personal representative
                        of the Brazilian Minister for Foreign Affairs at the Second Meeting of the
                        Ministers of Foreign Affairs.</note> reports there is talk in some quarters
                    Habana that “autonomy should be conceded existing colonies in America”. Aranha
                        <pb facs="0254" n="242" xml:id="pg_242"/> says that he disagrees with this.
                    He supports the Department’s position regarding the colonies.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
